www.foobar.com one-server infrastructure

COMPONENTS
- 1 server (IP: 8.8.8.8)
- Web server: Nginx
- Application server (runs the codebase)
- Application codebase
- Database: MySQL
- Domain: foobar.com with www A record → 8.8.8.8

FLOW
User types www.foobar.com → DNS resolves www A record to 8.8.8.8 →
Browser sends HTTP request to server → Nginx receives request →
forwards to application server → app executes code → queries MySQL →
response returned to user over HTTP/HTTPS

EXPLANATIONS

What is a server?
A server is a computer that provides services or resources to other
computers (clients) over a network. It runs continuously and waits
for incoming requests.

What is the role of the domain name?
The domain name (foobar.com) is a human-readable alias for the server
IP address. DNS translates www.foobar.com to 8.8.8.8 so users do not
need to remember IP addresses.

What type of DNS record is www?
www is an A record. It maps the hostname www.foobar.com directly to
the IPv4 address 8.8.8.8.

What is the role of the web server (Nginx)?
Nginx listens for incoming HTTP/HTTPS requests, serves static files
(HTML, CSS, images) directly, and forwards dynamic requests to the
application server.

What is the role of the application server?
The application server executes the business logic of the codebase,
processes dynamic requests, interacts with the database, and returns
generated responses to Nginx.

What is the role of the database (MySQL)?
MySQL stores and retrieves persistent data such as user accounts,
content, and transactions. The application server queries it using SQL.

How does the server communicate with the user?
The server communicates with the user's browser via HTTP (or HTTPS),
which runs over TCP/IP.

ISSUES

SPOF (Single Point of Failure):
There is only one server. If it goes down (hardware failure, crash),
the entire website becomes unavailable.

Downtime during maintenance:
Deploying new code or restarting Nginx brings the site down briefly.
There is no failover or zero-downtime deployment mechanism.
